<h1 class="mb-3">What is Check Yourself?</h1>

<h5 class="text-dark"><span class="fw-semibold">Check Yourself</span> is a tool designed to help you analyze written text.</h5>
<p class="mb-3 text-dark">
    It was created as a spin-off of the Africa Stereotype Scanner (ASTRSC). ASTRSC, developed in collaboration with journalists, scholars, and activists, scans written text for linguistic elements that contribute to stereotypes about Africa. During a community feedback session in February 2023, participants including Suzanne Temwa Gondwe Harris and Nanjala Nyabola raised important questions: Who decides which stereotypes the tool should scan? And who selects the words that contribute to specific stereotypes? Mel Bunce then suggested a tool that allows users to choose the words and frames for scanning, leading to the creation of <span class="fw-semibold">Check Yourself</span>.
 
</p>

<h5 class="text-dark">So, what is <span class="fw-bold">Check Yourself</span>?</h5>
<p class="mb-3 text-dark">
    Imagine you want to analyze news articles and track the frequency of certain words. With <span class="fw-semibold">Check Yourself</span>, simply create a list of words as a "<a href="/what-is-a-frame" class="link fw-semibold">frame</a>." Input the article you want to analyze, click scan, and the tool will highdark instances of those words in the text. If you need to scan for multiple sets of words, create different frames. You can download the results and frames for future use. 
</p>

